{"title_page": "Lyon Park Historic District", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Lyon Park Historic District\n  | nrhp_type = hd  | nocat = yes  \n  | designated_other1 = Virginia Landmarks Register\n  | designated_other1_date = May 19, 2003, March 10, 2008<ref name=\"VLR list\">{{cite web|title=Virginia Landmarks Register|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 000-7820\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | image = Lyon Park Historic District 01.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | location= Roughly bounded by 10th St. N, Arlington Blvd., and N. Irving St., [[Arlington, Virginia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|38|52|45|N|77|5|26|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Virginia#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1919}}\n  | architect = Lyon, Frank; Sunderland, Walter, et al.\n  | architecture = Queen Anne, Colonial Revival, et al.                      \n  | added = November 12, 2003\n  | area = {{convert|284.4|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 03000437<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Lyon Park Historic District''' is a national [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] and upper-class neighborhood located at [[Arlington County, Virginia]]. It contains 1,165 [[Contributing property|contributing buildings]] and 1 contributing site in a residential neighborhood in South Arlington. The area was platted between 1919 and 1951.  The dwelling styles include a variety of architectural styles, ranging from Craftsman-style bungalows dating from the 1920s to [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]]-style buildings dating from the 1930s and 1940s.  A number of [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne]] style dwellings erected prior to the platting of Lyon Park are also present.<ref name=VAnom>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-7820_Lyon_Park_Historic_District_2003_Final_Nomination.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Lyon Park Historic District |author=Jana E. Riggle |date=June 2003 }} and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/NR_Arlington_Lyon%20Park_Web_photographs.htm ''Accompanying four photos''] and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/South_Arlington_20101005.pdf ''Accompanying map''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926195857/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/South_Arlington_20101005.pdf |date=2012-09-26 }}</ref>\n\nIt was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2003.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n== Neighborhood Watch ==\nThe five founding members of the Lyon Park Historic District Neighborhood Watch created their coalition in early 2009 in order to deter crime, improve public safety, and encourage community building. Built on neighborhood pride, bravery, and sheer boredom, these community guardians were dedicated to their evening walks, using their flashlights to shatter the shadows of hooligans and criminals skittering through the dark corners of North Pershing Drive. Although they strived for safety and professionalism, this motley crew of vigilantes was not initially met with acceptance.\n\nBy mid-summer 2009 the Lyon Park Night Watch, as they self-deputized themselves, was constantly beaten down at local community meetings. \"All I can hear at night is the ice in their cups rattling,\" one disgruntled neighbor cried at the infamous July 24th meeting. As the ungrateful community members locked horns on how to officially disband the Night Watch, its founding members were out catching a band of local youths in the midst of the horrific act of hurling tissue paper atop the oldest oak in the neighborhood. \n\nAfter that night, no youth dared purchase a roll of any kind, whether it be toilet paper, jelly, or dinner. Henceforth, the Lyon Park Night Watch was official--supported not only by the mothers and fathers that wanted to keep their children safe, but also by the fear of all crooks and convicts in the 5-mile radius. \n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commonscat|Lyon Park Historic District}}\n\n{{Arlington County, Virginia}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Virginia}}\n\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Queen Anne architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n\n\n{{ArlingtonCountyVA-NRHP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Lyon Park Historic District\n  | nrhp_type = hd  | nocat = yes  \n  | designated_other1 = Virginia Landmarks Register\n  | designated_other1_date = May 19, 2003, March 10, 2008<ref name=\"VLR list\">{{cite web|title=Virginia Landmarks Register|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 000-7820\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | image = Lyon Park Historic District 01.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | location= Roughly bounded by 10th St. N, Arlington Blvd., and N. Irving St., [[Arlington, Virginia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|38|52|45|N|77|5|26|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Virginia#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1919}}\n  | architect = Lyon, Frank; Sunderland, Walter, et al.\n  | architecture = Queen Anne, Colonial Revival, et al.                      \n  | added = November 12, 2003\n  | area = {{convert|284.4|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 03000437<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Lyon Park Historic District''' is a national [[Historic district (United States)|historic district]] and upper-class neighborhood located at [[Arlington County, Virginia]]. It contains 1,165 [[Contributing property|contributing buildings]] and 1 contributing site in a residential neighborhood in South Arlington. The area was platted between 1919 and 1951.  The dwelling styles include a variety of architectural styles, ranging from Craftsman-style bungalows dating from the 1920s to [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]]-style buildings dating from the 1930s and 1940s.  A number of [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne]] style dwellings erected prior to the platting of Lyon Park are also present.<ref name=VAnom>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/000-7820_Lyon_Park_Historic_District_2003_Final_Nomination.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Lyon Park Historic District |author=Jana E. Riggle |date=June 2003 }} and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/NR_Arlington_Lyon%20Park_Web_photographs.htm ''Accompanying four photos''] and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/South_Arlington_20101005.pdf ''Accompanying map''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120926195857/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Arlington/South_Arlington_20101005.pdf |date=2012-09-26 }}</ref>\n\nIt was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2003.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commonscat|Lyon Park Historic District}}\n\n{{Arlington County, Virginia}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Virginia}}\n\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Queen Anne architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n\n\n{{ArlingtonCountyVA-NRHP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "W.W.Lyon.1919", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated to reflect neighborhood watch", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyon_Park_Historic_District"}
{"title_page": "Ning Jinsheng", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese engineer}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| name        = Ning Jinsheng\n| other_names = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1932|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Tianjin]], China\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2020|3|15|1932|10|22}}\n| death_place = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=it}}-->\n| fields      = [[Earth gravity]]\n| workplaces  = [[Wuhan University]]\n| patrons     = \n| alma_mater  = [[Tongji University]]\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| awards      = \n| thesis_title =  <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =  <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =  <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =  <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = {{ill|Xia Jianbai|zh|\u590f\u575a\u767d}}<br>{{ill|Wang Zhizhuo|zh|\u738b\u4e4b\u5353}}<br>Ye Xue'an ({{lang|zh|\u53f6\u96ea\u5b89}})\n| doctoral_students = [[Li Jiancheng (geodesist)|Li Jiancheng]]\n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| signature   =  <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =  <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes   = \n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u5b81|\u6d25|\u751f}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u5be7|\u6d25|\u751f}}\n|p = N\u00edng J\u012bnsh\u0113ng\n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Ning (surname)|Ning]]}} \n'''Ning Jinsheng''' ({{zh|s=\u5b81\u6d25\u751f|p=N\u00edng J\u012bnsh\u0113ng}}; October 22, 1932 \u2013 March 15, 2020) was a Chinese engineer who was a professor at [[Wuhan University]], a president of Wuhan University of Surveying and Mapping Technology, and an academician of the [[Chinese Academy of Engineering]] (CAE).<ref>{{cite news|author1=|url=https://tech.sina.com.cn/roll/2020-03-15/doc-iimxyqwa0697765.shtml |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5de5\u7a0b\u9662\u9662\u58eb\u5b81\u6d25\u751f\u5728\u6b66\u6c49\u901d\u4e16\uff1a\u4eab\u5e7488\u5c81 |work=sina |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nNing was born in [[Tianjin]], on October 22, 1932, while his [[Ancestral home (Chinese)|ancestral home]] was in [[Tongcheng County]], [[Anhui]].<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Chen Zhuo ({{lang|zh|\u9648\u5353}})|url=http://ah.sina.com.cn/news/2020-03-16/detail-iimxyqwa0747155.shtml |script-title=zh:\u7696\u7c4d\u4e2d\u56fd\u5de5\u7a0b\u9662\u9662\u58eb \u6b66\u6c49\u5927\u5b66\u6559\u6388\u5b81\u6d25\u751f\u901d\u4e16 |work=sina |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> In September 1951, he entered [[Tongji University]], where he studied surveying under {{ill|Xia Jianbai|zh|\u590f\u575a\u767d}}, {{ill|Wang Zhizhuo|zh|\u738b\u4e4b\u5353}}, and Ye Xue'an ({{lang|zh|\u53f6\u96ea\u5b89}}). After graduating in 1956, he was assigned to Wuhan Institute of Surveying and Mapping ({{lang|zh|\u6b66\u6c49\u6d4b\u91cf\u5236\u56fe\u5b66\u9662}}) as an assistant. In May 1966, during the [[Cultural Revolution]], he was forced to work in the dining room instead of teaching in classrooms. In August 1984, he was appointed vice-president of Wuhan University of Surveying and Mapping Technology ({{lang|zh|\u6b66\u6c49\u6d4b\u7ed8\u79d1\u6280\u5927\u5b66}}), rising to the president position in January 1988. In August 2000, Wuhan University of Surveying and Mapping Technology was merged into [[Wuhan University]], and he served as professor and doctoral supervisor of the university. On March 15, 2020, he died in Wuhan, Hubei, aged 87.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Guo Luyao ({{lang|zh|\u90ed\u8def\u7476}})|url=http://finance.sina.com.cn/manage/crz/2020-03-16/doc-iimxyqwa0756326.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5b81\u6d25\u751f\u901d\u4e16\uff1a\u575a\u6301\u4e0e5\u9662\u58eb\u5f00\u8bfe \u88ab\u79f0\u96c6\u9f50\u7b7e\u540d\u53ec\u5524\u795e\u9f99 |work=sina |publisher=China Youth News |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* 1995 Member of the [[Chinese Academy of Engineering]] (CAE)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Members of the Chinese Academy of Engineering (1995)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ning, Jinsheng}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Tianjin]]\n[[Category:Tongji University alumni]]\n[[Category:Wuhan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chinese Academy of Engineering]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese engineer}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| name        = Ning Jinsheng\n| other_names = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1932|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Tianjin]], China\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2020|3|15|1932|10|22}}\n| death_place = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=it}}-->\n| fields      = [[Earth gravity]]\n| workplaces  = [[Wuhan University]]\n| patrons     = \n| alma_mater  = [[Tongji University]]\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| awards      = \n| thesis_title =  <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =  <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =  <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =  <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = {{ill|Xia Jianbai|zh|\u590f\u575a\u767d}}<br>{{ill|Wang Zhizhuo|zh|\u738b\u4e4b\u5353}}<br>Ye Xue'an ({{lang|zh|\u53f6\u96ea\u5b89}})\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| signature   =  <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =  <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes   = \n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u5b81|\u6d25|\u751f}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u5be7|\u6d25|\u751f}}\n|p = N\u00edng J\u012bnsh\u0113ng\n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Ning (surname)|Ning]]}} \n'''Ning Jinsheng''' ({{zh|s=\u5b81\u6d25\u751f|p=N\u00edng J\u012bnsh\u0113ng}}; October 22, 1932 \u2013 March 15, 2020) was a Chinese engineer who was a professor at [[Wuhan University]], a president of Wuhan University of Surveying and Mapping Technology, and an academician of the [[Chinese Academy of Engineering]] (CAE).<ref>{{cite news|author1=|url=https://tech.sina.com.cn/roll/2020-03-15/doc-iimxyqwa0697765.shtml |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5de5\u7a0b\u9662\u9662\u58eb\u5b81\u6d25\u751f\u5728\u6b66\u6c49\u901d\u4e16\uff1a\u4eab\u5e7488\u5c81 |work=sina |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nNing was born in [[Tianjin]], on October 22, 1932, while his [[Ancestral home (Chinese)|ancestral home]] was in [[Tongcheng County]], [[Anhui]].<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Chen Zhuo ({{lang|zh|\u9648\u5353}})|url=http://ah.sina.com.cn/news/2020-03-16/detail-iimxyqwa0747155.shtml |script-title=zh:\u7696\u7c4d\u4e2d\u56fd\u5de5\u7a0b\u9662\u9662\u58eb \u6b66\u6c49\u5927\u5b66\u6559\u6388\u5b81\u6d25\u751f\u901d\u4e16 |work=sina |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> In September 1951, he entered [[Tongji University]], where he studied surveying under {{ill|Xia Jianbai|zh|\u590f\u575a\u767d}}, {{ill|Wang Zhizhuo|zh|\u738b\u4e4b\u5353}}, and Ye Xue'an ({{lang|zh|\u53f6\u96ea\u5b89}}). After graduating in 1956, he was assigned to Wuhan Institute of Surveying and Mapping ({{lang|zh|\u6b66\u6c49\u6d4b\u91cf\u5236\u56fe\u5b66\u9662}}) as an assistant. In May 1966, during the [[Cultural Revolution]], he was forced to work in the dining room instead of teaching in classrooms. In August 1984, he was appointed vice-president of Wuhan University of Surveying and Mapping Technology ({{lang|zh|\u6b66\u6c49\u6d4b\u7ed8\u79d1\u6280\u5927\u5b66}}), rising to the president position in January 1988. In August 2000, Wuhan University of Surveying and Mapping Technology was merged into [[Wuhan University]], and he served as professor and doctoral supervisor of the university. On March 15, 2020, he died in Wuhan, Hubei, aged 87.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Guo Luyao ({{lang|zh|\u90ed\u8def\u7476}})|url=http://finance.sina.com.cn/manage/crz/2020-03-16/doc-iimxyqwa0756326.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5b81\u6d25\u751f\u901d\u4e16\uff1a\u575a\u6301\u4e0e5\u9662\u58eb\u5f00\u8bfe \u88ab\u79f0\u96c6\u9f50\u7b7e\u540d\u53ec\u5524\u795e\u9f99 |work=sina |publisher=China Youth News |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* 1995 Member of the [[Chinese Academy of Engineering]] (CAE)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Members of the Chinese Academy of Engineering (1995)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ning, Jinsheng}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Tianjin]]\n[[Category:Tongji University alumni]]\n[[Category:Wuhan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chinese Academy of Engineering]]\n", "name_user": "Huangdan2060", "label": "safe", "comment": "| doctoral_students =Li Jiancheng", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ning_Jinsheng"}
{"title_page": "2020 New York City Subway fire", "text_new": "{{current}}\n{{short description|2020 New York City Subway fire}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = 2020 New York City Subway fire\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = 110th Street-Central Park North Station.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = [[Central Park North\u2013110th Street station]] where the incident took place.\n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = \n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = March 27, 2020\n| time                = 3:15 a.m.\n| location            = between [[96th Street (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|96th Street]] and [[Central Park North\u2013110th Street (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)|Central Park North\u2013110th Street]]\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = [[United States]]\n| line                = [[IRT Lenox Avenue Line]]\n| operator            = [[New York City Transit Authority]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| type                = [[Fire]]\n| cause               = Under Investigation, possible arson\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 1\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = \n| crew                = 2\n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 1\n| injuries            = 16 (4 serious)\n| damage              = Severe fire damage to several subway cars and additional damage to 110th Street station\n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = \n| route_map_state     = \n| route_map_name      = \n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nOn the early morning of March 27, 2020, at around 3:15 AM, a northbound [[2 (New York City Subway service)|2]] train of the [[New York City Subway]] caught fire as it entered the [[Central Park North\u2013110th Street station]] in [[Harlem]], [[Manhattan]]. The fire killed the operator, injured at least 16 others, and damaged the north part of the station and the train. MTA officials said the conductor and a MTA employee successfully evacuated passengers from the train and off the platform. Passengers and crew from a second train, behind the train with the fire, were also evacuated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/one-dead-least-16-hurt-new-york-city-subway-fire-n1170231|title=One dead, at least 16 hurt in New York City subway fire|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Press|first=Associated|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/new-york-man-killed-subway-fire|title=New York: man killed and at least a dozen hurt in subway fire, officials say|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Accident==\nOn the early morning hours of March 27, 2020, a northbound [[2 (New York City Subway service)|2]] train was operating its late night local run between [[Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College station]] and [[Wakefield\u2013241st Street station]]. The train consisted of ten [[R142 (New York City Subway car)|R142]] train sets numbered 6346-6350 and 6366-6370.<ref name=\"Fire\">{{cite tweet |number=1243649110491750403 |user=JMartinezNYC |title=Photos obtained by @THECITYNY of this morning\u2019s fatal subway fire at the Central Park North-110th Street station the level of destruction.|author=Jose Martinez |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TrainFire\">{{cite tweet |number=1244387678679904261 |user=TripleG_RTO |title=Train that was set on fire at 110 st RIP Train Operator Goble \ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe\ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe\ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe @vinbarone @AliBaumanTV @KatieLusso @clauirizarry\n|author=Gomez |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> While moving north between 96th Street and 110th Street, a fire erupted aboard the second car of the train, 6347, and the train arrived into 110th Street engulfed in flames. Firefighters responded to the fire around 3:18 am. It took 100 firefighters to control the fire. A northbound [[3 (New York City Subway service)|3]] train behind the 2 train was evacuated in the tunnel. At the time of the fire, there was extremely low visibility due to the intense smoke which also began to seep through the station entrances to 110th Street. After the fire was extinguished, it was revealed that 6347 had suffered severe fire damage, as well as additional fire and smoke damage to the 110th Street station.<ref name=\"Fire\"/>\n\nSixteen people were injured, with four suffering serious injuries. The motorman, identified as Garrett Goble, was found on the tracks and pronounced dead shortly after. He was the only fatality, and died after working to save all the passengers on the train.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Katersky |first1=Aaron |title=Motorman dead, dozens injured in suspicious Harlem subway fire |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/motorman-dead-dozens-injured-suspicious-harlem-subway-fire/story?id=69837299 |website=ABC |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nAdditional fires were reported at the [[86th Street station (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|86th Street]], [[96th Street station (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|96th Street]], and [[116th Street station (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)|116th Street]] stations around the same time, and because of this, the incident is currently being investigated as a possible [[arson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/ny-dead-injured-fire-moving-harlem-subway-20200327-bzasn2dwpvclzidv6pb7txz32e-story.html|title=Hero MTA train operator dies trying to evacuate commuters from Harlem subway fire, at least nine others hospitalized|last=Tracy|first=Thomas|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"nbcny-000\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/4-hurt-following-underground-fire-at-central-park-north-subway-station-fdny/2346682/|title=\u2018Hero\u2019 Train Conductor Dead, 16 Hurt in NYC Subway Fire; Blaze Probed as Suspicious: Officials|website=NBC New York|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> An \"apparently emotionally disturbed person\" is being questioned in connection to the 110th Street fire.<ref name=\"nbcny-000\"/> Authorities also reported a shopping cart was set on fire aboard the second car of the train.<ref>{{cite web |title=Police Investigating Deadly NYC Subway Fire As A Crime |url=https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/new-york-subway-fire-crime |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nTrain service along the [[IRT Lenox Avenue Line]] were suspended as a result of the incident. [[2 (New York City Subway service)|2]] trains operated along the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] from [[149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse station]] to [[Atlantic Avenue\u2013Barclays Center station]] before resuming regular service while [[3 (New York City Subway service)|3]] trains operated between [[New Lots Avenue station (IRT New Lots Line)|New Lots Avenue]] and [[96th Street station (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|96th Street]] and then via the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] to/from [[137th Street\u2013City College station|137th Street\u2013City College]] with service suspended between 96th Street and [[Harlem\u2013148th Street station]]. Shuttle buses operated along the closed stations. 86th Street and 96th Street stations were also temporarily closed in order to allow FDNY to continue their investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mymtaalerts.com/m?D8D31|title=MANH, 1 Train, FDNY Activity|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=mymtaalerts.com|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mymtaalerts.com/m?D8D32|title=UPDATED: BX, 3 Train, FDNY Activity|website=mymtaalerts.com|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Service along the IRT Lenox Avenue Line resumed on March 30 while bypassing [[Central Park North\u2013110th Street station]] for repairs. The NYPD released a picture of a \"person of interest\" in association with the fire two days later.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Barone |first1=Vincent |title=Police seek man in connection to fatal Harlem subway fire |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/29/police-seek-man-in-connection-to-fatal-harlem-subway-fire/ |website=New York Post |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> It is still unknown if the R142\u2019s involved (6346-6350 and 6366-6370) are scrapped.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|New York City}}\n* [[List of transportation fires]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{New York City Subway}}\n\n{{coord missing|New York (state)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New York City Subway fire, 2020}}\n[[Category:2020 fires]]\n[[Category:2020 in New York City]]\n[[Category:21st century in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Fires in New York City]]\n[[Category:Harlem]]\n[[Category:History of the New York City Subway]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Train and subway fires]]\n", "text_old": "{{current}}\n{{short description|2020 New York City Subway fire}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = 2020 New York City Subway fire\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = 110th Street-Central Park North Station.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = [[Central Park North\u2013110th Street station]] where the incident took place.\n<!--