 MTA officials said the conductor and a MTA employee successfully evacuated passengers from the train and off the platform. Passengers and crew from a second train, behind the train with the fire, were also evacuated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/one-dead-least-16-hurt-new-york-city-subway-fire-n1170231|title=One dead, at least 16 hurt in New York City subway fire|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Press|first=Associated|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/27/new-york-man-killed-subway-fire|title=New York: man killed and at least a dozen hurt in subway fire, officials say|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Accident==\nOn the early morning hours of March 27, 2020, a northbound [[2 (New York City Subway service)|2]] train was operating its late night local run between [[Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College station]] and [[Wakefield\u2013241st Street station]]. The train consisted of ten [[R142 (New York City Subway car)|R142]] train sets numbered 6346-6350 and 6366-6370.<ref name=\"Fire\">{{cite tweet |number=1243649110491750403 |user=JMartinezNYC |title=Photos obtained by @THECITYNY of this morning\u2019s fatal subway fire at the Central Park North-110th Street station the level of destruction.|author=Jose Martinez |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TrainFire\">{{cite tweet |number=1244387678679904261 |user=TripleG_RTO |title=Train that was set on fire at 110 st RIP Train Operator Goble \ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe\ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe\ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffe @vinbarone @AliBaumanTV @KatieLusso @clauirizarry\n|author=Gomez |date=March 29, 2020 |access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> While moving north between 96th Street and 110th Street, a fire erupted aboard the second car of the train, 6347, and the train arrived into 110th Street engulfed in flames. Firefighters responded to the fire ar