{"title_page": "Maria Saal", "text_new": "{{short description|Place in Carinthia, Austria}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name            = Maria Saal\n| native_name     = \n| settlement_type = \n<!-- Images     -->\n| image_skyline   = Maria Saal 22032007 01.jpg\n| imagesize       = \n| image_caption   = \n| image_shield    = Wappen at maria-saal.png\n| shield_size     = 80x110px\n| shield_link     = \n<!-- Maps           -->\n| pushpin_map         = Austria Carinthia#Austria\n| pushpin_mapsize     = 270\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of Maria Saal within Carinthia##Location of Maria Saal within Austria\n| image_map           = \n| mapsize             = \n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         = Location within [[Klagenfurt-Land]] district\n<!-- Location    -->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|46|41|N|14|21|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type  = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name  = {{AUT}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[States of Austria|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Carinthia]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[District (Austria)|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Klagenfurt-Land]]\n| parts_type        = \n| parts_style       = para\n| p1                = \n<!-- Leaders -->\n| leader_title  = [[Burgomaster|Mayor]]\n| leader_name   = Anton Schmidt ([[\u00d6VP]])\n| leader_party  = \n| leader_title1 = \n| leader_name1  = \n<!-- Statistics -->\n| area_footnotes   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_footnotes}}\n| area_total_km2   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_total_km2}}\n| area_metro_km2   = \n| elevation_m      = 505\n| elevation_max_m  = \n| elevation_min_m  = \n| population_as_of = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n| population_total = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_urban =  \n| population_metro =  \n| population_note  = \n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| established_title = \n| established_date  = \n| timezone          = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| timezone_DST      = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset        = +1\n| utc_offset_DST    = +2\n| registration_plate = \n| postal_code_type   = [[List of postal codes in Austria|Postal code]]\n| postal_code        = 9063\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in Austria|Area code]]\n| area_code      = 04223\n| website   = [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929014058/http://www.mariasaal.at/default.aspx?SIID=1&LAID=2 www.mariasaal.at]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Maria Saal''' ({{lang-sl|Gospa Sveta}}) is a [[market town]] in the district of [[Klagenfurt-Land]] in the [[Austria]]n state of [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]]. It is located in the east of the historic [[Zollfeld]] plain (''Gosposvetsko polje''), the wide valley of the [[Glan (Gurk)|Glan]] river. The municipality includes the [[Katastralgemeinden|cadastral communes]] of Kading, Karnburg, M\u00f6derndorf, Possau and St. Michael am Zollfeld.\n\n==History==\nThe Zollfeld valley has been a cultural and political centre since [[Celts|Celtic]] tribes settled in the region. When their kingdom of [[Noricum]] had become a province of the [[Roman Empire]] in 15 BC, Emperor [[Claudius]] had the city of [[Virunum]] erected as the province's capital at the foot of the nearby [[Magdalensberg]], where on the hill top a splendid Celtic settlement had already existed. Virunum  became a centre of [[early Christianity]] in the early 4th century as the [[Episcopal see|see]] of a bishop under the jurisdiction of the [[Patriarchate of Aquileia (Episcopal)|Patriarch of Aquileia]].\n[[File:Valvasor MARIA SAAL 1680 Kupferstich.jpg|thumb|left|Maria Saal with [[Duke's Chair]], engraving by [[Johann Weikhard von Valvasor]], 1680]]\nWhen pagan [[Slavic settlement of the Eastern Alps|Slavic tribes]] entered the region around 590, they settled in a place called Krnski Grad (German: Karnburg), close to Virunum, which became the administrative centre of their [[Carantania]] principality. Here the ritual of installing the [[prince]]s took place on the [[Prince's Stone]], the base of an ancient Roman [[Ionic order|Ionic]] column originating from Virunum. The ceremony was continued in the local dialect of the Slovene language long into the Middle Ages. After Duke [[Odilo, Duke of Bavaria|Odilo of Bavaria]] about 743 had vassalised the Carantanian prince Borut, the ritual was supplemented by a German-language ceremony at the [[Duke's Chair]], a double throne made of stone, which can still be seen near Maria Saal.\n\nThe second [[Christianization]] of the area began at about 767 under Bishop [[Vergilius of Salzburg]]. His missionary [[Modestus (Apostle of Carantania)|Modestus]] had the first church of the [[Assumption of Mary]] built at Maria Saal/Gospa Sveta, across the plain from Krnski Grad/Karnburg, as the centre of his missionary activities. ''S. Maria ad Carantanum'' was first mentioned in an 860 deed, probably a smallish wooden church that has vanished long since. From this bishop's church - by no means a cathedral in the modern sense of the word - [[Christianity]] was spread all over Carantania.\n\nAfter [[Charlemagne]] had finally deposed the Bavarian duke [[Tassilo III, Duke of Bavaria|Tassilo III]] in 787, Karnburg remained the political capital when Carantania became a [[march (territory)|march]] of the [[Francia|Frankish realm]]. The [[East Francia|East Frankish]] king [[Arnulf of Carinthia]] (\u2020 899), probably born in nearby [[Moosburg, Austria|Moosburg]], built a ''[[Kaiserpfalz]]'' here. In 893 he appointed the Bavarian count [[Luitpold, Margrave of Bavaria|Luitpold]] Margrave in the [[March of Carinthia]], his [[Luitpoldings|Luitpolding]] descendants also ruled as [[List of rulers of Bavaria|Bavarian dukes]].\n\nWhen Emperor [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Otto II]] deposed Duke [[Henry II, Duke of Bavaria|Henry II the Quarrelsome]] and finally separated Carinthia from [[History of Bavaria|Bavaria]] in 976, Karnburg also was the political centre of the [[Duchy of Carinthia|duchy]], a function that later was taken over by the ducal town of [[Sankt Veit an der Glan]], a few miles to the north, and finally in the 16th century by the City of [[Klagenfurt]] to the south.\n[[File:Maria Saal Kapuzinerstoeckl Dom und Dechantei W-Ansicht 03072017 0083.jpg|thumb|St Mary's Church]]\n\n==Church==\nMaria Saal is famous for its large [[pilgrimage]] church in seemingly transitional style from [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] to [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]]. Not much remains from the Romanesque church that had replaced the bishop's church of Modestus and his successors. The present fortified church building goes back to the mid-15th century and is in high Gothic style, actually  reconstructed within 20 years  after the big fire of 1669.\n\nIn view of the church's predecessor, which, as the church of Bishop Modestus, was the religious center of Carinthia in the 8th century and practically an [[episcopal see]] until 945, the present church is popularly still called a \"Dom\", i.e. \"[[cathedral]]\", which it, of course, has never been. The [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] sarcophagus  beneath the church is said to contain the remains of Modestus. Still today, however, it is a major [[pilgrimage]] site for both German- and Slovene-speaking Carinthians and even for Slovene nationals.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\n===Church Bells===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! # !! Foundry !! Cast year !! Mass !! Tone !! Diameter !! Name\n|-\n| 1. || Mathias Landsmann || 1687 || {{convert|6608|kg|0|abbr=on}} || Fis\u00b0 || {{convert|222|cm|0|abbr=on}} || Maria Saalerin\n|-\n| 2. || Grassmayr || 1925|| {{convert|2098|kg|0|abbr=on}} || cis' ||  ||\n|-\n| 3. || Grassmayr || 1972|| {{convert|1310|kg|0|abbr=on}} || dis' ||  ||\n|-\n| 4. || Lorenz Pez || 1670 || ~{{convert|1100|kg|0|abbr=on}} || f' ||  ||\n|-\n| 5. || Grassmayr || 1972|| {{convert|560|kg|0|abbr=on}} || gis' ||  ||\n|-\n| 6. || Grassmayr || 1972|| {{convert|390|kg|0|abbr=on}} || b' ||  ||\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Friedrich Welwitsch]], [[Botany|botanist]], born February 25, 1806 in Maria Saal, died October 20, 1872 in [[London]].\n*[[Felix Oschmautz]], [[Canoe slalom|slalom canoeist]], born July 18, 1999 in Maria Saal.\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Austria}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\n\nMaria Saal is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Aquileia]] ([[Italy]])\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Forgaria nel Friuli]] ([[Italy]])\n*{{flagicon|SVN}} [[Gornji Grad, Slovenia|Gornji Grad]] ([[Slovenia]])\n\n==References==\n\n===Literature===\n\"Maria Saal\", Venice 2002, Alessandra Bettini Silvia Carraro;\nTesi di laurea\n\n===Notes===\n{{Commons}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Carinthia-geo-stub}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Cities and towns in Klagenfurt-Land (district)}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Klagenfurt-Land District]]\n[[Category:Maria Saal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Place in Carinthia, Austria}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name            = Maria Saal\n| native_name     = \n| settlement_type = \n<!-- Images     -->\n| image_skyline   = Maria Saal 22032007 01.jpg\n| imagesize       = \n| image_caption   = \n| image_shield    = Wappen at maria-saal.png\n| shield_size     = 80x110px\n| shield_link     = \n<!-- Maps           -->\n| pushpin_map         = Austria Carinthia#Austria\n| pushpin_mapsize     = 270\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of Maria Saal within Carinthia##Location of Maria Saal within Austria\n| image_map           = \n| mapsize             = \n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         = Location within [[Klagenfurt-Land]] district\n<!-- Location    -->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|46|41|N|14|21|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type  = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name  = {{AUT}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[States of Austria|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Carinthia]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[District (Austria)|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Klagenfurt-Land]]\n| parts_type        = \n| parts_style       = para\n| p1                = \n<!-- Leaders -->\n| leader_title  = [[Burgomaster|Mayor]]\n| leader_name   = Anton Schmidt ([[\u00d6VP]])\n| leader_party  = \n| leader_title1 = \n| leader_name1  = \n<!-- Statistics -->\n| area_footnotes   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_footnotes}}\n| area_total_km2   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_total_km2}}\n| area_metro_km2   = \n| elevation_m      = 505\n| elevation_max_m  = \n| elevation_min_m  = \n| population_as_of = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n| population_total = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_urban =  \n| population_metro =  \n| population_note  = \n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| established_title = \n| established_date  = \n| timezone          = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| timezone_DST      = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset        = +1\n| utc_offset_DST    = +2\n| registration_plate = \n| postal_code_type   = [[List of postal codes in Austria|Postal code]]\n| postal_code        = 9063\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in Austria|Area code]]\n| area_code      = 04223\n| website   = [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929014058/http://www.mariasaal.at/default.aspx?SIID=1&LAID=2 www.mariasaal.at]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Maria Saal''' ({{lang-sl|Gospa Sveta}}) is a [[market town]] in the district of [[Klagenfurt-Land]] in the [[Austria]]n state of [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]]. It is located in the east of the historic [[Zollfeld]] plain (''Gosposvetsko polje''), the wide valley of the [[Glan (Gurk)|Glan]] river. The municipality includes the [[Katastralgemeinden|cadastral communes]] of Kading, Karnburg, M\u00f6derndorf, Possau and St. Michael am Zollfeld.\n\n==History==\nThe Zollfeld valley has been a cultural and political centre since [[Celts|Celtic]] tribes settled in the region. When their kingdom of [[Noricum]] had become a province of the [[Roman Empire]] in 15 BC, Emperor [[Claudius]] had the city of [[Virunum]] erected as the province's capital at the foot of the nearby [[Magdalensberg]], where on the hill top a splendid Celtic settlement had already existed. Virunum  became a centre of [[Early Christianity]] in the early 4th century as the [[Episcopal see|see]] of a bishop under the jurisdiction of the [[Patriarchate of Aquileia (Episcopal)|Patriarch of Aquileia]].\n[[File:Valvasor MARIA SAAL 1680 Kupferstich.jpg|thumb|left|Maria Saal with [[Duke's Chair]], engraving by [[Johann Weikhard von Valvasor]], 1680]]\nWhen pagan [[Slavic settlement of the Eastern Alps|Slavic tribes]] entered the region around 590, they settled in a place called Krnski Grad (German: Karnburg), close to Virunum, which became the administrative centre of their [[Carantania]] principality. Here the ritual of installing the [[prince]]s took place on the [[Prince's Stone]], the base of an ancient Roman [[Ionic order|Ionic]] column originating from Virunum. The ceremony was continued in the local dialect of the Slovene language long into the Middle Ages. After Duke [[Odilo, Duke of Bavaria|Odilo of Bavaria]] about 743 had vassalised the Carantanian prince Borut, the ritual was supplemented by a German-language ceremony at the [[Duke's Chair]], a double throne made of stone, which can still be seen near Maria Saal.\n\nThe second [[Christianization]] of the area began at about 767 under Bishop [[Vergilius of Salzburg]]. His missionary [[Modestus (Apostle of Carantania)|Modestus]] had the first church of the [[Assumption of Mary]] built at Maria Saal/Gospa Sveta, across the plain from Krnski Grad/Karnburg, as the centre of his missionary activities. ''S. Maria ad Carantanum'' was first mentioned in an 860 deed, probably a smallish wooden church that has vanished long since. From this bishop's church - by no means a cathedral in the modern sense of the word - [[Christianity]] was spread all over Carantania.\n\nAfter [[Charlemagne]] had finally deposed the Bavarian duke [[Tassilo III, Duke of Bavaria|Tassilo III]] in 787, Karnburg remained the political capital when Carantania became a [[march (territory)|march]] of the [[Francia|Frankish realm]]. The [[East Francia|East Frankish]] king [[Arnulf of Carinthia]] (\u2020 899), probably born in nearby [[Moosburg, Austria|Moosburg]], built a ''[[Kaiserpfalz]]'' here. In 893 he appointed the Bavarian count [[Luitpold, Margrave of Bavaria|Luitpold]] Margrave in the [[March of Carinthia]], his [[Luitpoldings|Luitpolding]] descendants also ruled as [[List of rulers of Bavaria|Bavarian dukes]].\n\nWhen Emperor [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Otto II]] deposed Duke [[Henry II, Duke of Bavaria|Henry II the Quarrelsome]] and finally separated Carinthia from [[History of Bavaria|Bavaria]] in 976, Karnburg also was the political centre of the [[Duchy of Carinthia|duchy]], a function that later was taken over by the ducal town of [[Sankt Veit an der Glan]], a few miles to the north, and finally in the 16th century by the City of [[Klagenfurt]] to the south.\n[[File:Maria Saal Kapuzinerstoeckl Dom und Dechantei W-Ansicht 03072017 0083.jpg|thumb|St Mary's Church]]\n\n==Church==\nMaria Saal is famous for its large [[pilgrimage]] church in seemingly transitional style from [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] to [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]]. Not much remains from the Romanesque church that had replaced the bishop's church of Modestus and his successors. The present fortified church building goes back to the mid-15th century and is in high Gothic style, actually  reconstructed within 20 years  after the big fire of 1669.\n\nIn view of the church's predecessor, which, as the church of Bishop Modestus, was the religious center of Carinthia in the 8th century and practically an [[episcopal see]] until 945, the present church is popularly still called a \"Dom\", i.e. \"[[cathedral]]\", which it, of course, has never been. The [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] sarcophagus  beneath the church is said to contain the remains of Modestus. Still today, however, it is a major [[pilgrimage]] site for both German- and Slovene-speaking Carinthians and even for Slovene nationals.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\n===Church Bells===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! # !! Foundry !! Cast year !! Mass !! Tone !! Diameter !! Name\n|-\n| 1. || Mathias Landsmann || 1687 || {{convert|6608|kg|0|abbr=on}} || Fis\u00b0 || {{convert|222|cm|0|abbr=on}} || Maria Saalerin\n|-\n| 2. || Grassmayr || 1925|| {{convert|2098|kg|0|abbr=on}} || cis' ||  ||\n|-\n| 3. || Grassmayr || 1972|| {{convert|1310|kg|0|abbr=on}} || dis' ||  ||\n|-\n| 4. || Lorenz Pez || 1670 || ~{{convert|1100|kg|0|abbr=on}} || f' ||  ||\n|-\n| 5. || Grassmayr || 1972|| {{convert|560|kg|0|abbr=on}} || gis' ||  ||\n|-\n| 6. || Grassmayr || 1972|| {{convert|390|kg|0|abbr=on}} || b' ||  ||\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Friedrich Welwitsch]], [[Botany|botanist]], born February 25, 1806 in Maria Saal, died October 20, 1872 in [[London]].\n*[[Felix Oschmautz]], [[Canoe slalom|slalom canoeist]], born July 18, 1999 in Maria Saal.\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Austria}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\n\nMaria Saal is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Aquileia]] ([[Italy]])\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Forgaria nel Friuli]] ([[Italy]])\n*{{flagicon|SVN}} [[Gornji Grad, Slovenia|Gornji Grad]] ([[Slovenia]])\n\n==References==\n\n===Literature===\n\"Maria Saal\", Venice 2002, Alessandra Bettini Silvia Carraro;\nTesi di laurea\n\n===Notes===\n{{Commons}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Carinthia-geo-stub}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Cities and towns in Klagenfurt-Land (district)}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Klagenfurt-Land District]]\n[[Category:Maria Saal]]\n", "name_user": "Chessrat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Saal"}
{"title_page": "Constellations (play)", "text_new": "{{Infobox play\n| name       = Constellations \n| image      = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt  = \n| caption    = \n| writer     = [[Nick Payne]]\n| chorus     = \n| characters = Roland<br>Marianne\n| mute       = \n| setting    = \n| premiere   = {{Start date|2012|1|19}} \n| place      = [[Royal Court Theatre]] Upstairs<br>[[London]]\n| orig_lang  = English\n| series     = \n| subject    = \n| genre      = \n| web        = \n}}\n\n'''''Constellations''''' is a [[two-hander]] play by the English playwright [[Nick Payne]].\n\n==Productions==\n''Constellations'' premiered at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in January 2012, with [[Rafe Spall]] and [[Sally Hawkins]] in the lead roles and direction by Michael Longhurst.<ref>Shenton, Mark. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/sally-hawkins-and-rafe-spall-to-star-in-nick-paynes-constellations-at-londo-185075 \"Sally Hawkins and Rafe Spall to Star in Nick Payne's 'Constellations' at London's Royal Court\"] playbill.com, 1 December 2011</ref> The play received strong reviews from critics and subsequently transferred to the [[Duke of York's Theatre]] in the [[West End theatre|West End]] in November 2012.<ref>[http://www.royalcourttheatre.com/whats-on/constellations-west-end \"''Constellations'' Listing, Duke of York's Theatre\"] \nroyalcourttheatre.com, accessed 6 May 2015</ref> The reviewer for ''The Guardian'' wrote \"For all its teasing razzle-dazzle, though, it is the human warmth of the writing and acting that ensures the play never slides into tricksiness.\"<ref>Gardner, Lyn. [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2012/nov/18/constellations-review \"Review\"] ''The Guardian'', 18 November 2012</ref> In November 2012 ''Constellations'' was named the winner of the best play category at the [[Evening Standard Theatre Awards]], making the 29-year-old Payne the youngest winner of the award.<ref>[http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2012/11/nick-paynes-constellations-wins-best-play-at-es-theatre-awards/ \"Nick Paynes Constellations Wins Best Play at ES Theatre-Awards\"] ''The Stage'', 2012</ref> The play toured the UK, starting in May 2015 at Woking's New Victoria Theatre.<ref>Shenton, Mark. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/constellations-will-tour-the-u.k-343111 \" 'Constellations' Will Tour the U.K.\"] playbill.com, 03 March 2015</ref> \n\nThe play premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in a [[Manhattan Theatre Club]] production at the [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]] on January 13, 2015 and closed on 15 March 2015. The cast starred [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] (in his Broadway debut) and [[Ruth Wilson]].<ref>Purcell, Carey. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/jake-gyllenhaal-and-ruth-wilson-explore-constellations-on-broadway-337444 \"Jake Gyllenhaal and Ruth Wilson Explore 'Constellations' on Broadway\"] playbill.com, 16 December 2014</ref> Ruth Wilson received a nomination for the 2015 [[Tony Award]], Best Performance By a Leading Actress in a Play.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [https://archive.is/20150428125601/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/69th-annual-tony-awards-nominations-announced-347781 \"69th Annual Tony Awards Nominations Announced!\"] Playbill.com, 28 April 2015</ref> The play received three Drama League Award nominations: Best Play, Best Actor, Gyllenhaal, and Best Actress, Wilson.<ref>[http://www.manhattantheatreclub.com/2014-15-season/constellations/  \" 'Constellations' Listing\"] manhattantheatreclub.com, accessed 6 May 2015</ref> A production opened on February 10, 2016 at the Boise Contemporary Theater in Boise, ID, running through March 5, and starring Dwayne Blackaller and Tiara Thompson and directed by Tracy Sunderland.\n\nIn January 2013 Payne revealed that a film adaptation was under way.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/lift-off-for-the-writer-with-stars-in-his-eyes-8435913.html ''Independent'' profile of Nick Payne, 2 January 2013.]</ref> That plan has since been shelved.\n\nIn 2016 the Canadian English-language premiere was co-produced by [[Montreal]]'s [[Centaur Theatre]] and [[Toronto]]\u2019s [[Canadian Stage Company]]. The show was directed by legendary Canadian director Peter Hinton and starred [[Cara Ricketts]] and Graham Cuthbertson.<ref>https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/theatre/constellations-is-a-quantum-love-story-that-flits-between-universes</ref>\n\nThe 2016 Studio Theatre production was nominated for 6 awards at the 2017 Helen Hayes Awards in Washington, D.C.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/nominations-for-the-2017-helen-hayes-awards/2017/02/06/0ac9101c-ec85-11e6-b4ff-ac2cf509efe5_story.html</ref> The production won 2 awards, with Tom Patterson receiving the Robert Prosky Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Play and Lily Balatincz receiving Outstanding Lead Actress in a Play.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/theater_dance/the-2017-helen-hayes-awards-recipients/2017/05/15/8e1e90b2-397a-11e7-a058-ddbb23c75d82_story.html</ref><ref>https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/2017-Helen-Hayes-Award-Winners-Announced-Updating-Live-20170515</ref>\n\nThe play has premiered in Los Angeles at the Geffen Playhouse with [[Ginnifer Goodwin]] and [[Allen Leech]] and director Giovanna Sardelli.<ref>{{cite web|title=Constellations|url=http://www.geffenplayhouse.org/constellations|publisher=Geffen Playhouse|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe play premiered in Perth, Western Australia in June 2018 with Paul Davey and Madelaine Jones and directed by Brendan Ellis.\n\nIn November 2015, the Chinese-language premiere is directed and translated by [[Wang Chong (director)|Wang Chong]] in Beijing. He uses 13 cameras on the stage to conceptualize the play into a \"stage movie\" with 50 long takes as the 50 scenes. The result is a very intimate cinematic experience in theater. A real hamster is also put on the stage as if it is the god of time and universe who dictates the cuts of the \"movie\" and the possibilities of life. Because of the show's success, the actress Wang Xiaohuan is noted by ''[[The Beijing News]]'' as The Young Theater Artist of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/beijing/2015-11/06/content_22390752.htm|title=Play of scenarios in love seeks to bemuse Beijing[1]|last=\u80e1\u54f2|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\nin 2018 the work premiered in Lima Peru, from January to March, under the direction of Rodrigo Falla, and with the performances of Jesus Neyra and Gisela Ponce De Le\u00f3n.\nThe work was a resounding success in Lima, having good reviews, was so successful then it was presented in the province of Tacna and in the plazuelas de las artes of the municipality of Lima.\n\n==Plot Summary==\nThe play follows Roland, a beekeeper, and Marianne, a cosmologist through their romantic relationship. Marianne often waxes poetic about cosmology, quantum mechanics, string theory and the belief that there are multiple universes that pull people's lives in various directions. This is reflected in the play's structure as brief scenes are repeated, often with different outcomes. \n\nRoland and Marianne meet at a barbecue and become romantically involved. After they've moved in together, a confession of infidelity causes them to break up. After some time, they run in to each other at a ballroom dancing class, resume their relationship, and eventually marry. Marianne begins to forget words and has trouble typing. She is told by her doctor that she has a tumor in her frontal lobe and has less than a year to live. She eventually seeks [[assisted suicide]] abroad with Roland's support. The play ends with a flashback to the scene where Roland and Marianne rekindle their relationship in the dance class.\n\n==Publication==\nSeveral versions of the play have been published in the United Kingdom and the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title=Constellations. Revised Edition. |last=Payne |first=Nick |publisher=Faber & Faber |location=London |date=2012 |oclc=862086790 |isbn=9780571301966 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Constellations. First American Edition. |last=Payne |first=Nick |publisher=Faber & Faber |location=New York |date=2014 |oclc=906061703 |isbn=9780865477711}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 plays]]\n[[Category:English plays]]\n[[Category:Two-handers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox play\n| name       = Constellations \n| image      = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt  = \n| caption    = \n| writer     = [[Nick Payne]]\n| chorus     = \n| characters = Roland<br>Marianne\n| mute       = \n| setting    = \n| premiere   = {{Start date|2012|1|19}} \n| place      = [[Royal Court Theatre]] Upstairs<br>[[London]]\n| orig_lang  = English\n| series     = \n| subject    = \n| genre      = \n| web        = \n}}\n\n'''''Constellations''''' is a [[two-hander]] play by the English playwright [[Nick Payne]].\n\n==Productions==\n''Constellations'' premiered at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in January 2012, with [[Rafe Spall]] and [[Sally Hawkins]] in the lead roles and direction by Michael Longhurst.<ref>Shenton, Mark. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/sally-hawkins-and-rafe-spall-to-star-in-nick-paynes-constellations-at-londo-185075 \"Sally Hawkins and Rafe Spall to Star in Nick Payne's 'Constellations' at London's Royal Court\"] playbill.com, 1 December 2011</ref> The play received strong reviews from critics and subsequently transferred to the [[Duke of York's Theatre]] in the [[West End theatre|West End]] in November 2012.<ref>[http://www.royalcourttheatre.com/whats-on/constellations-west-end \"''Constellations'' Listing, Duke of York's Theatre\"] \nroyalcourttheatre.com, accessed 6 May 2015</ref> The reviewer for ''The Guardian'' wrote \"For all its teasing razzle-dazzle, though, it is the human warmth of the writing and acting that ensures the play never slides into tricksiness.\"<ref>Gardner, Lyn. [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2012/nov/18/constellations-review \"Review\"] ''The Guardian'', 18 November 2012</ref> In November 2012 ''Constellations'' was named the winner of the best play category at the [[Evening Standard Theatre Awards]], making the 29-year-old Payne the youngest winner of the award.<ref>[http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2012/11/nick-paynes-constellations-wins-best-play-at-es-theatre-awards/ \"Nick Paynes Constellations Wins Best Play at ES Theatre-Awards\"] ''The Stage'', 2012</ref> The play toured the UK, starting in May 2015 at Woking's New Victoria Theatre.<ref>Shenton, Mark. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/constellations-will-tour-the-u.k-343111 \" 'Constellations' Will Tour the U.K.\"] playbill.com, 03 March 2015</ref> \n\nThe play premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in a [[Manhattan Theatre Club]] production at the [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]] on January 13, 2015 and closed on 15 March 2015. The cast starred [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] (in his Broadway debut) and [[Ruth Wilson]].<ref>Purcell, Carey. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/jake-gyllenhaal-and-ruth-wilson-explore-constellations-on-broadway-337444 \"Jake Gyllenhaal and Ruth Wilson Explore 'Constellations' on Broadway\"] playbill.com, 16 December 2014</ref> Ruth Wilson received a nomination for the 2015 [[Tony Award]], Best Performance By a Leading Actress in a Play.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [https://archive.is/20150428125601/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/69th-annual-tony-awards-nominations-announced-347781 \"69th Annual Tony Awards Nominations Announced!\"] Playbill.com, 28 April 2015</ref> The play received three Drama League Award nominations: Best Play, Best Actor, Gyllenhaal, and Best Actress, Wilson.<ref>[http://www.manhattantheatreclub.com/2014-15-season/constellations/  \" 'Constellations' Listing\"] manhattantheatreclub.com, accessed 6 May 2015</ref> A production opened on February 10, 2016 at the Boise Contemporary Theater in Boise, ID, running through March 5, and starring Dwayne Blackaller and Tiara Thompson and directed by Tracy Sunderland.\n\nIn January 2013 Payne revealed that a film adaptation was under way.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/lift-off-for-the-writer-with-stars-in-his-eyes-8435913.html ''Independent'' profile of Nick Payne, 2 January 2013.]</ref> That plan has since been shelved.\n\nIn 2016 the Canadian English-language premiere was co-produced by [[Montreal]]'s [[Centaur Theatre]] and [[Toronto]]\u2019s [[Canadian Stage Company]]. The show was directed by legendary Canadian director Peter Hinton and starred [[Cara Ricketts]] and Graham Cuthbertson.<ref>https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/theatre/constellations-is-a-quantum-love-story-that-flits-between-universes</ref>\n\nThe 2016 Studio Theatre production was nominated for 6 awards at the 2017 Helen Hayes Awards in Washington, D.C.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/nominations-for-the-2017-helen-hayes-awards/2017/02/06/0ac9101c-ec85-11e6-b4ff-ac2cf509efe5_story.html</ref> The production won 2 awards, with Tom Patterson receiving the Robert Prosky Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Play and Lily Balatincz receiving Outstanding Lead Actress in a Play.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/theater_dance/the-2017-helen-hayes-awards-recipients/2017/05/15/8e1e90b2-397a-11e7-a058-ddbb23c75d82_story.html</ref><ref>https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/2017-Helen-Hayes-Award-Winners-Announced-Updating-Live-20170515</ref>\n\nThe play has premiered in Los Angeles at the Geffen Playhouse with [[Ginnifer Goodwin]] and [[Allen Leech]] and director Giovanna Sardelli.<ref>{{cite web|title=Constellations|url=http://www.geffenplayhouse.org/constellations|publisher=Geffen Playhouse|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe play premiered in Perth, Western Australia in June 2018 with Paul Davey and Madelaine Jones and directed by Brendan Ellis.\n\nIn November 2015, the Chinese-language premiere is directed and translated by [[Wang Chong (director)|Wang Chong]] in Beijing. He uses 13 cameras on the stage to conceptualize the play into a \"stage movie\" with 50 long takes as the 50 scenes. The result is a very intimate cinematic experience in theater. A real hamster is also put on the stage as if it is the god of time and universe who dictates the cuts of the \"movie\" and the possibilities of life. Because of the show's success, the actress Wang Xiaohuan is noted by ''[[The Beijing News]]'' as The Young Theater Artist of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/beijing/2015-11/06/content_22390752.htm|title=Play of scenarios in love seeks to bemuse Beijing[1]|last=\u80e1\u54f2|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\nin 2018 the work premiered in Lima Peru, from January to March, under the direction of Rodrigo Falla, and with the performances of Jesus Neyra and Gisela Ponce De Le\u00f3n.\nThe work was a resounding success in Lima, having good reviews, was so successful then it was presented in the province of Tacna and in the plazuelas de las artes of the municipality of Lima (Place where the best works of Peru are presented free of charge financed by the municipality).\n\n==Plot Summary==\nThe play follows Roland, a beekeeper, and Marianne, a cosmologist through their romantic relationship. Marianne often waxes poetic about cosmology, quantum mechanics, string theory and the belief that there are multiple universes that pull people's lives in various directions. This is reflected in the play's structure as brief scenes are repeated, often with different outcomes. \n\nRoland and Marianne meet at a barbecue and become romantically involved. After they've moved in together, a confession of infidelity causes them to break up. After some time, they run in to each other at a ballroom dancing class, resume their relationship, and eventually marry. Marianne begins to forget words and has trouble typing. She is told by her doctor that she has a tumor in her frontal lobe and has less than a year to live. She eventually seeks [[assisted suicide]] abroad with Roland's support. The play ends with a flashback to the scene where Roland and Marianne rekindle their relationship in the dance class.\n\n==Publication==\nSeveral versions of the play have been published in the United Kingdom and the United States.<ref>{{cite book |title=Constellations. Revised Edition. |last=Payne |first=Nick |publisher=Faber & Faber |location=London |date=2012 |oclc=862086790 |isbn=9780571301966 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Constellations. First American Edition. |last=Payne |first=Nick |publisher=Faber & Faber |location=New York |date=2014 |oclc=906061703 |isbn=9780865477711}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 plays]]\n[[Category:English plays]]\n[[Category:Two-handers]]\n", "name_user": "Gentizol", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProductions:Not a verifiable claim", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constellations_(play)"}
{"title_page": "Shirlene Coelho", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = \n| name             = \n| image            = Shirlene Coelho Rio2016cr.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Coelho at the 2016 Paralympics\n| birth_name       = \n| fullname         = \n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = \n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = {{birth-date and age|19 February 1981}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} !-->\n| country          = \n| sport            = [[Paralympic athletics]]\n| event            = [[Javelin throw]], [[discus throw]], [[shot put]]\n| collegeteam      = \n| club             = \n| team             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| disability_class = [[T37 (classification)|T37]]\n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n| pb               = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport|Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw F35-38|Javelin F35-38]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F37/38]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F37]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus F37/F38]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F37]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Shirlene Coelho''' (born 19 February 1981) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]]. She competed in the [[T37 (classification)|T37]] javelin throw, discus throw and shot put at the 2008, 2012 and 2016 Paralympics. At the 2016 Rio Paralympic games, she won a gold medal in Women's Javelin F37 and won a silver medal in Women's Discus Throw F38. At the 2012 London Paralympic games, she won a gold medal at the Women's Javelin F37/38 event. At the 2008 Beijing Paralympic games, she won a silver medal at the Women's Javelin F35-38.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/shirlene-coelho|title=Shirlene Coelho - Athletics {{!}} Paralympic Athlete Profile|website=International Paralympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>[https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/shirlene-coelho Shirlene Coelho]. rio2016.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Shirlene Coelho}}\n* {{IPC athlete|id=shirlene-coelho|old_id=869686}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coelho, Shirlene}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-athletics-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = \n| name             = \n| image            = Shirlene Coelho Rio2016cr.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Coelho at the 2016 Paralympics\n| birth_name       = \n| fullname         = \n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = \n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = {{birth-date and age|19 February 1981}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} !-->\n| country          = \n| sport            = [[Paralympic athletics]]\n| event            = [[Javelin throw]], [[discus throw]], [[shot put]]\n| collegeteam      = \n| club             = \n| team             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| disability_class = [[T37 (classification)|T37]]\n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n| pb               = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport|Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw F35-38|Javelin F35-38]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F37/38]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F37]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus F37/F38]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F37]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Shirlene Coelho''' (born 19 February 1981) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]]. She competed in the [[T37 (classification)|T37]] javelin throw, discus throw and shot put at the 2008, 2012 and 2016 Paralympics. At the 2016 Rio Paralympic games, she won a gold medal in Women's Javelin F37 and won a silver medal in Women's Discus Throw F38. At the 2012 London Paralympic games, she won a gold medal at the Women's Javelin F37/38 event. At the 2008 Beijing Paralympic games, she won a silver medal at the Women's Javelin F35-38.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/shirlene-coelho|title=Shirlene Coelho - Athletics {{!}} Paralympic Athlete Profile|website=International Paralympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> <ref>[https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/shirlene-coelho Shirlene Coelho]. rio2016.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Shirlene Coelho}}\n* {{IPC athlete|869686}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coelho, Shirlene}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-athletics-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shirlene_Coelho"}
